At my return home l repose myself a while3 then I take a walk; and after that, read aloud and with emphasis some Greek or Latin oration, not so much ior the sake of strengthening my elocution as my digestion; though indeed the voice at the same time finds its account in this practice. Then l walk again, am anointed, take my exercises, and go into the bath. At supper, if I have only my wife, or a few friends ,with me, some author is read to us; and alter supper we are entertained either with music, or an interlude.
